[normal]Written evidence from[bold] [bold]King’s Fund (PEX0033)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The King’s Fund is an independent charity working to improve health and health care in England. We help to shape policy and practice through research and analysis; develop individuals, teams and organisations; promote understanding of the health and social care system; and bring people together to learn, share knowledge and debate. Our vision is that the best possible care is available to all.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The NHS is 
[normal]more than two and a half years th
[normal]rough the 
[normal]most significant period of financial constraint in its history
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]with the 
[normal]prospects beyond 2015 looking even more challenging
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]At the aggregate level,
[normal] 
[normal]it has
[normal] 
[normal]so far 
[normal]managed reasonably well, 
[normal]in large part due to continued 
[normal]pay restraint and reductions in the tariff. However, 
[normal]this masks growing pressures within the system, with 
[normal]an increasing number of providers now in deficit
[normal] and 
[normal]many struggling to meet the 
[normal]A&amp;E waiting time target.
[normal] The reality for many NHS organisations is that they now face a difficult choice between 
[normal]maintaining
[normal] quality of care and balancing the books.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
