[normal]The plans being made to meet the Nicholson Challenge and whether the NHS is succeeding in making efficiency gains rather than cuts[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Since April 2011, The King’s Fund has published a quarterly monitoring report which analyses NHS performance against key indicators and tracks progress in 
[normal]improving productivity
[normal] based on a regular survey of NHS finance directors. Although the survey is 
[normal]not a representative sample
[normal], 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]some 
[normal]caution should be exercised in comparing results
[normal] between quarters
[normal], it does provide valuable insight into how the NHS is responding to the Nicholson Challenge.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The reports 
[normal]show
[normal] that NHS organisations made good progress in meeting productivity targets
[normal] during the first two years of the Nicholson Challenge
[normal]. In 2011/12,
[normal] an average saving of 4.7 per cent was reported by those responding to 
[normal]our
[normal] survey, against an average cost improvement programme (CIP) target of 5.1 per cent. In 2012/13, an average saving of 4.6 per cent was reported against an average CIP
[normal] target of 4.9 per cent. These findings are 
[normal]broadly 
[normal]consistent with other evidence about the 
[normal]progress 
[normal]made in meeting the Nicholson Challenge
[normal],
[normal] including the National Audit Office’s assessment of 
[normal]savings
[normal] made in 2011/12.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]However, our 
[normal]two 
[normal]most recent reports reveal a significant 
[normal]fall 
[normal]in
[normal] confidence among those surveyed about whether CIP targets can 
[normal]continue to be met
[normal]. 
[normal]Our most recent report, in September 2013, found that only a third 
[normal]of NHS trust finance directors were confident of meeting 
[normal]an average
[normal] CIP target for 2013/14 
[normal]of 4.9 per cent. 
[normal]This 
[normal]contrast
[normal]s with
[normal] around 70 per cent who were confident of meeting their target for 
[normal]2012/13 
[normal]in
[normal] our
[normal] February report
[normal]. This 
[normal]reinforc
[normal]es
[normal] warnings that 
[normal]the 
[normal]quick wins
[normal] have been identified and that 
[normal]savings will become progressively harder to achieve over time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CCG finance leads - surveyed for the first time for our September report – were much more confident
[normal] than their counterparts in NHS trusts
[normal], with nearly 70 per cent expecting to meet an average 
[normal]QIPP 
[normal]target of 2.5 per cent in 2013/14. 
[normal]NHS England and CCGs are forecasting a combined surplus of £596 million, although the number of CCGs predicting a deficit has increased from nine to 24.
[normal] 
[normal]With NHS England in particular still finding its feet, 
[normal]it will be vital to maintain financial control -
[normal] NHS England 
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]expecting to spend £318 million more than planned on direct commissioning and is now 
[normal]forecasting a £93 million deficit in its commissioning budget, mainly as a result of higher than anticipated expenditure on specialist services
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Overall, t
[normal]his 
[normal]suggest
[normal]s that 
[normal]the strain is
[normal] being felt most in the provider sector, which is not surprising gi
[normal]ven the year-on-year reductions in the tariff
[normal] and other pressures they are facing
[normal] (see below)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]On the prospect
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]for
[normal] meeting the target 
[normal]t
[normal]o deliver £20 billion in productivity improvements 
[normal]across the NHS 
[normal]by 2015,
[normal] only 10 per cent of those surveyed for our most recent report rated the chances as better than 50/50, with 
[normal]the majority (56 per cent) identifying a high or very high risk the target will not be met.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We 
[normal]note the assurances given to the Committee’s previous inquiry and the findings of the National Audit Office report that
[normal] the bulk of the savings made in 2011/12 were recurrent.
[normal] Nevertheless, we 
[normal]remain concerned that 
[normal]a significant element
[normal] of the progress so 
[normal]far has been delivered through
[normal] 
[normal]pay restraint, reductions in the tariff and cuts in management costs 
[normal]rather than genuin
[normal]e improvements in productivity. We also reiterate our concern that too much emphasis has been placed on generating financial savings, rather than on improving 
[normal]the 
[normal]quality 
[normal]of services for patients
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]P
[normal]ay rises for most NHS staff 
[normal]frozen for two years from 2011/12 and 
[normal]limited to
[normal] 1 per cent in 2013/14.
[normal] It remains to be seen whether the government is successful in deferring the planned 1 per cent pay rise 
[normal]due 
[normal]in April 2014. 
[normal]Opportunities remain to reduce the costs associated with the use of agency staff, locums and staff sickness. 
[normal]However,
[normal] pay restraint i
[normal]s
[normal] not a long term substitute for efficiency gain. With staff costs making up the bulk of the NHS budget and significant pressures on providers to maintain staffing levels following the shocking failures of care highlighted by the Francis report, there is little or no 
[normal]further 
[normal]room for manoeuvre in reducing staff costs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10)
[normal] 
[normal]Alongside this, year-on-year reductions in the tariff mean that it 
[normal]will have
[normal] been cut by nearly 7 per cent in real terms by 201
[normal]4
[normal]/1
[normal]5
[normal], increasing pressures on providers
[normal]. As the Committee pointed out in its previous report, the tariff is a blunt instrument for driving productivity improvements which does little to drive efficiencies among commissioners. 
[normal]With providers coming under increasing pressure, 
[normal]the
[normal] potential 
[normal]to 
[normal]reduc
[normal]e
[normal] 
[normal]it further
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] limit
[normal]ed
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11)
[normal] 
[normal]M
[normal]ajor reconfigurations of services are essential to improve quality of care
[normal] and have the potential to improve financial sustainability (although they often result in significant short term costs, 
[normal]as is
[normal] the case with the proposed changes to services in South London and Mid Staffordshire)
[normal]. 
[normal]However, 
[normal]progress continues to be slow and has been hampered by notable setbacks such as the failure to bring the long-running review of children’s heart surgery to a conclusion. The picture is further complicated by the 
[normal]increased involvement of the competition authorities in decisions about mergers and service changes. There are clearly lessons to be learned for the NHS from the Competition Commission’s recent decision to reject the proposed merger between Bournemouth and Poole hospitals. However, the risk is that this and other decisions 
[normal]result in
[normal] competition law 
[normal]being seen as
[normal] an impediment to service change
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12)
[normal] 
[normal]We remain concerned about the lack of capacity in the new health system 
[normal]to undertake large-scale reorganisations across wide geographical areas, especially in London, where the need for change is particularly urgent. We have proposed that 
[normal]NHS England's London office takes on a city-wide planning role, working with CCGs, and that hospitals work together in large-scale networks based on the three existing academic science networks 
[normal]to drive change. This would have the benefit of ensuring that major changes to services are overseen by the most experienced leaders and is 
[normal]an approach we 
[normal]believe
[normal] could be replicated elsewhere in the country.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13)
[normal] 
[normal]The Department of Health has previously indicated that 20 per cent of the productivity improvements needed to meet the £20 billion target will come from transformational change, with the bulk of this due to be delivered during the second half of the Nicholson Challenge period. 
[normal]Given the difficulties experienced so far in delivering transformational change, the lack of capacity for driving large scale 
[normal]reconfigurations
[normal], the additional complexity created by the interventions of the competition authorities and the political difficulty of agreeing changes 
[normal]to services 
[normal]in the run up to a General Election, 
[normal]the risk is that
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]any 
[normal]change will 
[normal]continue to be 
[normal]incremental 
[normal]and fragmented
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]when 
[normal]it needs to be urgent
[normal] and substantial
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effectiveness of the mechanisms by which resources are distributed geographically in the NHS[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]14)
[normal] 
[normal]NHS England is currently review
[normal]ing
[normal] the NHS allocations process, having rejected 
[normal]proposed 
[normal]changes to the 
[normal]current 
[normal]allocations 
[normal]formula as being inconsistent with its duty to reduce health inequalities. 
[normal]While recent debate has largely focused on the relative weight 
[normal]that should be 
[normal]given to age a
[normal]nd deprivation in the formula, more fundamental questions should be asked about whether the current process, which has remained largely unchanged since the 1970s, is fit for purpose.
[normal] 
[normal]At the heart of this is whether the resource allocation process is simply a mechanism for distributing funding
[normal] or 
[normal]should be 
[normal]a
[normal] more
[normal] active policy tool
[normal] for supporting wider NHS objectives
[normal]. 
[normal]As we set out in a report on this earlier this year, 
[normal]there is 
[normal]significant 
[normal]scope for it to 
[normal]be used 
[normal]as the latter
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15)
[normal] 
[normal]In the short term, immediate improvements could be made to reduce 
[normal]the 
[normal]complexity
[normal] of the current formula
[normal], increase transparency and improve
[normal] the way that need is estimated
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The review s
[normal]hould also 
[normal]examine
[normal] the 
[normal]operation of the 
[normal]‘pace of change’ adjustment 
[normal](previously decided by ministers, now by NHS England) which is 
[normal]built in to the process to 
[normal]prevent areas being destabilised by 
[normal]large
[normal] year-on-year swings in funding. In practice, this has reduced the impact of efforts to reallocate funding and insulated areas from change.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The prospects for the long term viability of NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]16)
[normal] 
[normal]Despite the challenging financial environment, 
[normal]NHS
[normal] 
[normal]providers have
[normal] so far held up 
[normal]reasonably 
[normal]well at the aggregate level
[normal]. Overall, the NHS in England reported a surplus of just over £2 billion in 2012/13. Our latest quarterly monitoring report found that nearly 
[normal]90 per cent of NHS trust finance directors and CCG finance leads surveyed expect to break even or record a surplus in 2013/14. However, the
[normal]se
[normal] figures obscure 
[normal]the fact that 
[normal]an increasing
[normal] number of trusts 
[normal]are struggling - seven of 42 NHS trust finance directors reported that they are forecasting a deficit.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17)
[normal] 
[normal]These findings are 
[normal]echo
