[normal] Smaller hospitals face particular challenges because they have a higher proportion of fixed costs and lower margin non-elective work. We note that Monitor is looking at the issues faced by smaller providers - we will be undertaking our own work in this area too.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19)
[normal] 
[normal]An added pressure for many acute trusts is 
[normal]caused by 
[normal]CCGs seek
[normal]ing
[normal] to shift outpatient activity in
[normal]to
[normal] community settings. While this can make care more accessible to patients, evidence suggests that initiatives 
[normal]to move care closer to home can 
[normal]drive up costs. 
[normal]M
[normal]uch greater scrutiny of commissioning strategies 
[normal]is needed 
[normal]to ensure that they reduce costs for 
[normal]health economies
[normal] as a whole.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20)
[normal] 
[normal]With 
[normal]a growing
[normal] number of trusts in deficit, others may be forced to follow the recent example of Barts 
[normal]which has been forced to cut staff, including 161 nursing posts, in the face of significant financial difficulties
[normal].
[normal] Meanwhile, many hospitals are struggling to 
[normal]meet 
[normal]the fo
[normal]ur hour A&amp;E waiting time target, underlining how difficult it will be for providers to continue to
[normal] maintain quality of care and balance the books.
[normal] 
[normal]There are also significant pressures in the mental health sector, with recent evidence suggesting that more than 1,700 mental health beds have been closed since 2011.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21)
[normal] 
[normal]The pressure will increase in 2015/16 following confirmation of another year of essentially flat funding and the announcement of the new £3.8 billion Integration Transformation Fund
[normal] (ITF)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]While 
[normal]this provides
[normal] 
[normal]an 
[normal]opportunity to drive 
[normal]forward 
