[normal]The impact on adult social care of the 2010 Spending Review settlement [bold]and ability of local authorities to make efficiency savings[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]23)
[normal] 
[normal]While the government’s decision to allocate additional resources to adult social care in the 2010 spending review was welcome, this has been more than offset by an overall reduction in financial support to local government of 
[normal]more than
[normal] 30 per cent. 
[normal]2
[normal]013/14 is the fourth consecutive year 
[normal]that 
[normal]local authorities
[normal] [bold]have reduced 
[normal]social care 
[normal]budgets, with a planned reduction of £795
[normal] million
[normal] contributing
[normal] to
[normal] a cumulative reduction of £2.68
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]illion
[normal] over the past three years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]24)
[normal] 
[normal]Although c
[normal]ouncils 
[normal]have a strong track record of delivering efficiency savings,
[normal] 
[normal]it 
[normal]is clear that 
[normal]their room for manoeuvre is 
[normal]now severely
[normal] limited, 
[normal]with £104
[normal] 
[normal]m
[normal]illion
[normal] of this year’s savings coming from the
[normal] direct withdrawal of services.
[normal] 87 per cent of councils now only respond to needs classified as substantial or critical under the Fair Access to Care (FACS) criteria. 
[normal]The decision in the 2013 Spending Round to impose a further reduction in grant funding of 10 per cent in 2015/16 will add to these pressures. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25)
[normal] 
[normal]As a result, t
[normal]he number of 
[normal]older 
[normal]people receiving publicly funded services has 
[normal]fallen 
[normal]by 
[normal]26
[normal] per cent since
[normal] 
[normal]2009/10, with an equivalent reduction of 21 per cent among working age adults over the same period.
[normal] Given the overriding imperative to provide care 
[normal]closer
[normal] 
[normal]to 
[normal]home and reduce the need for 
[normal]residential care and 
[normal]hospital admissions, it is particularly worrying that the 
[normal]largest 
[normal]reduction has been in the use of community-based services such as home care (down 25
[normal] per cent
[normal]) 
[normal]compared to nursing home care (down 
[normal]4
[normal] per cent) and residential care (down 1.7 per cent
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]26)
[normal] 
[normal]Since the Committee’s previous report, t
[normal]he government
[normal] has 
[normal]announced its decision
[normal] 
[normal]to implement the 
[normal]Dilnot Commission’s 
[normal]proposals
[normal], albeit with a higher cap 
[normal]on individual costs 
[normal]than the Commission recommended of £72,000. We welcome this as 
[normal]a 
[normal]significant 
[normal]milestone and a 
[normal]stepping stone to wider r
[normal]eform. 
[normal]However, i
[normal]mplementing the proposals 
[normal]will be challenging, with high risks
[normal] 
[normal]of confu
[normal]sion, complexity and complaints.
[normal] 
[normal]Without a major public awareness campaign, there is a real danger that many people will see the reforms as worse 
[normal]than
[normal] the current system, rather than an improvement on it
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27)
[normal] 
[normal]Implementing the 
[normal]Dilnot Commission
[normal]’s recommendations will not solve the social care funding challenge. As the Commission
[normal] concluded 
[normal]‘…
[normal] 
[normal]the government must devote greater resources to the adult social care system. As well as funding for new reforms, additional public funding for the means-tested system is urgently required’.
[normal] 
[normal]The central challenge is to assess the total quantity of resources needed to ensure that people have access to the right level of support
[normal]. For many people it is eligibility for help, not protection from co
[normal]sts
[normal] that is the primary issue. Setting the national eligibility threshold at the moderate level under the FACS criteria would increase the number of people helped by 23 per cent. However, at an estimated cost of £2 billion, it is hard to see this happening in the current financial climate. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]28)
[normal] 
[normal]The combination of unremitting financial and demographic pressures is undermining the government’s aim of putting social care on a stable footing through the Care Bill and the additional resources from the NHS. The House of Lords Committee on Public Services and Demographic Change was not exaggerating when it concluded that the social care system is in crisis.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The [bold]impact on NHS plans of decisions made by local authorities and the [bold]use of the additional funding for social care [bold]from[bold] the NHS budget[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]29)
[normal] 
[normal]The 2010 Spending Review announced that £1 billion would be transferred to local authorities from the NHS 
[normal]over the four years to 2014/15, with further transfers of 
