[normal]Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]34)
[normal] 
[normal]The Committee’s previous report emphasised the need to increase the scale and pace of integrated care. 
[normal]Since then, the government has signalled a more ambitious approach to delivering integrated care with 
[normal]key national bodies
[normal] signed up to a shared definition and commitment on integrated care, the creation of the ITF and the recent announcement 
[normal]that 
[normal]14 pioneer areas 
[normal]will
[normal] lead the way in developing integrated care.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35)
[normal] 
[normal]Integrated care not only improves patient outcomes and experience, but also offers significant opportunities to make more efficient use of resources by reducing waste, duplication and fragmentation. However, it is important to recognise that transformational change take
[normal]s
[normal] time to demonstrate results. The 
[normal]potential 
[normal]for integrated care 
[normal]to deliver financial savings remains to be seen, and there may be a need to invest in new models of care before resources can be released from existing models. 
[normal]&#xa0;
